The issue you're experiencing is likely due to a combination of problems in your JavaScript and Django view code. The cart item is being deleted on the server, but the client-side behavior (removing the item from the UI and showing the success message) isn't working as expected. Here's a step-by-step analysis and solution:

Issues Identified
Success Message Not Showing:
The Toast.fire call in the success callback of the AJAX request is not displaying the "Item deleted" message. This could be due to:
The Toast object (likely from a library like SweetAlert) not being properly initialized.
The AJAX response not being processed correctly.
The console.log(response) in the success callback can help verify if the response is received correctly, but you haven't mentioned seeing the log, so the success callback might not be executing.
Spinner Keeps Spinning:
The beforeSend function sets the button's HTML to a spinning icon (<i class="fas fa-spinner fa-spin ms-2"></i>), but there's no code to revert it back after the request completes (whether successful or not). This leaves the spinner stuck.
Item Not Disappearing Without Reload:
The line $('.item_div_' + item_id).addClass('d-none') is supposed to hide the deleted item, but it’s not working. This could be due to:
The success callback not being triggered.
The item_id not matching the class item_div_{{i.id}} in the HTML.
A JavaScript error halting execution before this line.
Response Handling:
The Django view returns a JsonResponse with total_cart_items and cart_sub_total, but the client-side code expects these fields to update the UI. If the response isn't received or parsed correctly, the UI won't update.
Potential Server-Side Issue:
The view calculates total_cart_items as a queryset (Cart.objects.filter(...)) but uses it as a number in the response. This will cause an error when the client tries to use response.total_cart_items as a number.
AJAX Request:
The AJAX request doesn't specify the method (e.g., POST or GET). By default, jQuery's $.ajax uses GET, which aligns with your view's use of request.GET.get(), but it's good to be explicit.
There's no error handling for the AJAX request, so if it fails (e.g., due to a server error), the spinner will keep spinning, and no feedback is provided to the user.
